# TypeScript Standards

## Context

- Applied to all TypeScript files
- Enforces proper handling of type errors
- Critical for code quality and type safety

## Requirements

- NEVER use `@ts-ignore` or `@ts-expect-error` unless explicitly directed
- Always fix type errors properly
- If unable to fix type error, ask for help

## Examples

<example type="invalid">
```typescript
// @ts-ignore
function processData(data: any) {
  return data.map(item => item.value);
}
```
Hides legitimate type issues instead of fixing them.
</example>

<example type="valid">
```typescript
function processData<T extends { value: string }>(data: T[]) {
  return data.map(item => item.value);
}
```
Properly defines types for compile-time safety.
</example>

<danger>
  `@ts-ignore` bypasses compile-time checking, hiding issues and creating runtime errors.
</danger>
